<article>
    <h1>Ur&#xAD;ban so&#xAD;lu&#xAD;tions and sus&#xAD;tain&#xAD;abil&#xAD;ity</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201212/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-12"><time>2020-12-12</time></a>
        - <span>THE BIG STORY</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>• Sin­ga­pore had over­come its wa­ter chal­lenges through in­vest­ments made in wa­ter tech­nol­ogy in its in­fancy.</p>
    <p>• But with cli­mate change threat­en­ing the sup­ply of other re­sources and high­light­ing the need to curb emis­sions, the coun­try is also look­ing to sci­ence to ad­dress th­ese chal­lenges.</p>
    <p>Ex­am­ple: De­car­bon­i­sa­tion – meth­ane crack­ing (En­ergy Re­search In­sti­tute @NTU)</p>
    <p>• Meth­ane crack­ing is a process that breaks down meth­ane into hy­dro­gen and solid car­bon with­out pro­duc­ing any car­bon diox­ide.</p>
    <p>• Hy­dro­gen pro­duced can be used as a low-car­bon fuel for power gen­er­a­tion.</p>
    <p>• Solid car­bon can be re­cy­cled as car­bon nan­otubes in high­per­for­mance ma­te­ri­als, or as part of build­ing ma­te­ri­als.</p>
    <p>• The NTU team is cur­rently lead­ing the re­search ef­fort with Sem­b­corp In­dus­tries to de­velop a cost-ef­fec­tive, ro­bust and re­gen­er­a­ble cat­a­lyst and re­ac­tor to drive the meth­ane crack­ing process</p>
    <p>To tackle such com­plex, cross-cut­ting chal­lenges, we must also look for so­lu­tions be­yond the nat­u­ral sciences and en­gi­neer­ing. We will tap other dis­ci­plines, such as so­cial and be­havioural sciences, since in­flu­enc­ing hu­man be­hav­iour is key to cre­at­ing real change.</p>
    <p>MIN­IS­TER FOR SUS­TAIN­ABIL­ITY AND THE EN­VI­RON­MENT GRACE FU</p>

